由于若干州面临与升降冠状病毒相关的公共卫生限制的批评，一项研究发布了星期五，证实了国家强加的面具授权和本地的用餐限制有助于缓慢Covid-19的传播。
  在疾病控制和预防中心发表的研究和第39次发病率和死亡率每周报告，看了在3月1日期间县级Covid-19案件和死亡的国家发行的面具任务和本地的影响12月31日。
     它发现掩码任务与＆＃34相关联;统计上有效＆＃34;每日Covid-19案例和死亡增长率在实施后20天内降低。相比之下，在重新开放后41至100天的日常病例增加，允许本地用餐有关，每日患者的增加，每日死亡增长率增加61至100天。
  ＆＃34;需要通用面膜使用和限制任何本地餐厅用餐的政策是减少SARS-COV-2，＆＃34的暴露和传输的全面策略的重要组成部分;研究作者写道。 ＆＃34;如果在美国的高度传输SARS-COV-2变体的出现，这种努力越来越重要。＆＃34;
  包括CDC在内的公共卫生专家长期推荐的通用掩蔽，避免了不必要的室内空间来减轻Covid-19的传播，而新发现增加了越来越多的证据，即这种措施是有效的。
      德克萨斯州和密西西比州州长宣布的研究员来回发布，他们将消除对企业的面具任务和能力限制，直接矛盾，在CDC指导中保持课程，因为国家对抗高度传染性变异的赛道让人口接种疫苗。
  最近几天，更多的州被搬回限制。康涅狄格州康涅狄格州康涅狄格州周四宣布，该国将在本月晚些时候提升餐馆和其他企业的能力限制，同时保持其面具授权和某些其他要求。周五，亚利桑那州＆＃39;州长签署了一项行政命令，消除了业务占用限制，距离和屏蔽协议仍然存在。 
德克萨斯州和密西西比州的州长表示，下降案例计数和加速疫苗的速度意味着个人应该能够做出关于Covid-19预防措施的决定。星期三拜登总统抨击那些国家＆＃39;决定回滚限制，称之为＆＃34;尼安德特思想。＆＃34;
  CDC导演Rochelle Walensky博士周三告诉NPR，最近对病毒的进展可能是停滞不前的，而未来几个月将在确定其课程方面发挥关键作用。与最近的Covid-19简报一样，她鼓励美国人遵循公共卫生指导，如屏蔽和社会疏散，即使它们不是强制性的。
    在白宫Covid-19响应小组在周五的回应小组简报，Walensky指出这项研究远离第一个展示面具佩戴和内部用餐风险的好处。
  ＆＃34;本报告是一个批判提醒，在社区的当前Covid-19水平和更多传播病毒变体的持续传播 - 现在在48个国家检测到 - 严格后，预防措施仍然是投入结束必不可少的对此大流行，＆＃34;她说。 ＆＃34;它还用作过早提升这些预防措施的警告。＆＃34;
     她补充说，这种情况和死亡是＆＃34;仍然太高，＆＃34;并达到了一个多星期。案例计数继续每天波动约60％至70千，确认每日死亡徘徊在2,000左右。
  简报官员注意到，虽然返回日常活动的想法可能听起来很有吸引力，但美国 - 现在的欧洲 - 已经看到了预防措施升力时的情况飙升。
  Andy Slavitt是白宫Covid-19回应团队的高级顾问，敦促人们戴面具＆＃34;不是永远的，但现在。＆＃34; 
＆＃34;这不仅仅是谨慎的公共卫生专家的声音，＆＃34; 他说。 ＆＃34;这是想要仍然开放的业务，以及在去年的两个缔约方的许多公共官员都在说。＆＃34;

note_en:
As several states face criticism for lifting coronavirus-related public health restrictions, a study published Friday confirms that state-imposed mask mandates and on-premises dining restrictions help slow the spread of COVID-19.
  The  study, published in the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention&#39;s Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report, looked at the impact of state-issued mask mandates and on-premises dining on county-level COVID-19 cases and deaths between March 1 and Dec. 31.
     It found that mask mandates were associated with &#34;statistically significant&#34; decreases in daily COVID-19 case and death growth rates within 20 days of implementation. In contrast, allowing on-premises dining was associated with an increase in daily cases 41 to 100 days after reopening, and an increase in daily death growth rates after 61 to 100 days.
  &#34;Policies that require universal mask use and restrict any on-premises restaurant dining are important components of a comprehensive strategy to reduce exposure to and transmission of SARS-CoV-2,&#34; the study authors wrote. &#34;Such efforts are increasingly important given the emergence of highly transmissible SARS-CoV-2 variants in the United States.&#34;
  Public health experts including the CDC have long recommended universal masking and avoiding nonessential indoor spaces to mitigate the spread of COVID-19, and the new findings add to a growing  body of evidence that such measures are effective.
      The study&#39;s release comes days after the governors of  Texas and Mississippi announced they would eliminate mask mandates and capacity limits on businesses, in direct contradiction of CDC guidance to  stay the course with such restrictions as the country races against highly infectious variants to get the population vaccinated.
  More states have moved to roll back restrictions in recent days. Connecticut&#39;s governor  announced on Thursday that the state will lift capacity limits on restaurants and other businesses later this month, while keeping its mask mandate and certain other requirements in place. And on Friday, Arizona&#39;s governor signed an  executive order eliminating business occupancy limits, with distancing and masking protocols to remain in place.
     The governors of Texas and Mississippi  said that falling case counts and the  accelerating pace of vaccinations mean that individuals should be able to make their own decisions about COVID-19 precautions. President Biden on Wednesday  slammed those states&#39; decision to roll back restrictions, calling it &#34;Neanderthal thinking.&#34;
  CDC Director Dr. Rochelle Walensky  told NPR on Wednesday that recent progress against the virus may be stalling, and the next few months will play a pivotal role in determining its course. As in recent COVID-19 briefings, she encouraged Americans to follow public health guidance like masking and social distancing even if they are not mandatory.
    At White House COVID-19 Response Team briefing on Friday, Walensky noted this study is far from the first to demonstrate the benefits of mask wearing and risks of in-person dining.
  &#34;This report is a critical reminder that with the current levels of COVID-19 in communities and the continued spread of more transmissible virus variants — which have now been detected in 48 states — strictly following prevention measures remains essential for putting an end to this pandemic,&#34; she said. &#34;It also serves as a warning about prematurely lifting these prevention measures.&#34;
     She added that cases and deaths are &#34;still too high,&#34; and have plateaued for more than a week. Case counts continue to fluctuate around 60 to 70 thousand per day, with confirmed daily deaths hovering around 2,000.
  Briefing officials noted that while the idea of getting back to everyday activities may sound appealing, both the U.S. —  and now Europe — have seen that cases surge when prevention measures lift.
  Andy Slavitt, senior adviser on the White House COVID-19 Response Team, urged people to wear a mask &#34;not forever, but for now.&#34;
  &#34;This is not just the voice of cautious public health experts,&#34; he said. &#34;It is what businesses who want to remain open, and many public officials, of both parties, who have lived through the last year are saying.&#34;
